<rating>5< /rating><gmapID>0x80dd271f323e1611:0xdc929c8d6106129a</gmapID><userid>108009001755178578051</userid>< review>
Arguably one of the most prominent ans influential Buddhist congregations in the West. I mean the Dalai Lama came and spoke on a 100 degree weekend for the Temple's grand opening. Drawing over 100,000 attendees. The presiding Venerable Monk refused to charge or collect admission. The main prayer hall has high vaulted ceilings, state of the art A/V, and an adjoining mixed usage space that holds charitable events, as a dining hall for parishioners, and in house FTA television studio and production space.<//review>

< Text>
First time there and better than I expected! Not big on Christian music, but the band is very good and I found myself swaying and moving to the songs. The other patrons seemed nice and ranged in age from young to old. However it seemed made up of young families, and young and middle aged adults mostly. They have a strong youth ministry, if that's important to you. We had the opportunity to hear the youth pastor that Sunday, and I must admit I was a little disappointed we wouldn't be hearing from the principal pastor... BUT it didn't last long because the youth pastor was GREAT and had a great message. I definitely recommend you slip on in if you're the slightest bit curious. Dress code is casual though some did dress up. And feel free to bring you cup of joe in - I wasn't sure so I left mine in the car, but tons of folks had brought in theirs.<//Text>

<Rating>1< /Rating>< text>
I would say the negative reviews are accurate and consistent in regards to the customer service. First, let's start with the store:
The associates seem nice but when it comes to product knowledge or inventory they are clueless. They do seem to be pushy, especially when it comes to delivery. They wanted an additional $180 for "white glove" delivery. The manager, who apparently has to approve EVERY transaction because of the discounts, was relentless with delivery. I asked him why I would spend more for delivery when I was already spending so much for the furniture in the first place. He actually said, "Don't you want to guarantee safe delivery of your new couch? Besides, if you don't pay for the white glove service and a part is missing or delivered damaged, you'll have to drive everything back to Stockton yourself." I looked at him and asked him, "Doesn't Ashley sell quality products? Do they hire bad drivers? If I'm having to question the delivery based upon whether I spend more for delivery or not then maybe I shouldn't buy from Ashley in the first place. Total scam. Anyways, I decline the white glove service and the ridiculous add-on warranty (another scam).
My delivery was set for April 22 (we went into the store on March 22...yes a month long wait because it was on back order) but were okay with it at the time. It gave us time to make arrangements for the removal of our old furniture. April 22 arrives and no phone call. We called the 800 number and they informed us that our couch was on back order and wouldn't arrive for another month! No courtesy phone call to give us a heads up or anything. They said if we had an issue with it we'd have to contact the store. Horrible customer service.
I called the store and spoke with a salesperson. I explained the situation and told them I wanted to cancel my order. The salesperson tried talking me out of it and when I said my mi d was already made up, she said she couldn't cancel the order, one the manager could. Of course. She also said the manager was busy and could call us back. I told her to either get the manager on the phone now or I'm coming down to the store. After about a15 minute wait the manager finally got on. I explained to him the story (third time I had to retell the story) and told him just to cancel it. He offered me an additional $200 off. Now wait...where was that discount when he was asking me about delivery? Anything to save a transaction I guess. Scam. I told him I was insulted by the offer and to cancel my order. He said okay. As he was canceling the order he actually asked me if anything had been delivered. His exact words were, "So, are you sure nothing was delivered?" I asked him, "You're kidding me, right? You think I'd waste my time with all of this if something was delivered?"
He finished up the cancellation and I received an email shortly after. He did apologize, which was fine even though I know it wasn't his fault directly or the stores....unless of course they weren't honest with me in the first place and lied about the original date of delivery (which, after reading numerous reviews here, is very possible).
Looooong story short: Bad customer service + delayed/back order fiasco = Horrible experience
I can't recommend Ashley Furniture in Colma after the nightmare we went through.< /text>

<Text>I was told my new couch would be delivered in 6 weeks, and maybe less, when I bought and paid for it in early February 2021.

Six weeks later I called and I was told that they had no idea when it would arrive in the warehouse, but that their best guess was a mid-April delivery, a full eight weeks after I paid for it.  I would not have bought it had I been told that it would take this long, and I imagine their management knows that.

I started writing this review as I've been on hold for over 30 minutes waiting for a supervisor to take my call so I can escalate for a resolution.  It took ten minutes for the first person I talked to pick up the phone when I first called at 1pm on a Thursday.  I'm actually now live-reviewing my experience in the hopes that somebody at Ashley HomeStore actually reviews this and responds.

D'Ariel is who helped me first and was very friendly and patient, and she created a case number for me for my unknown deliver date a month-and-a-half after I paid for it.  I thanked her for her help and suggested that she might want to start looking for a new job, because businesses that operate this poorly are usually going out of business.

We still have furniture to buy for our bedroom and dining room, but we're not going to spend a single dollar here ever again.  I encourage you to shop somewhere else yourself.

D'Lecia was the supervisor who was supposed to pick up the phone; it took 42 minutes before I was transferred to her finally, but was then put on hold again and sent to Angela, another customer service person.

I was put on hold again after 47 minutes, and then the salesperson who originally sold me the couch, Michael, answered after 50 minutes.

Michael remembered me, I explained what was happening and that I was very upset.

Ken was the manager who finally addressed my concern once Michael escalated to him.  He told me that my deliver date was April 16th, more than two months after I paid for my couch.

Ken blamed Coronavirus for the trouble and delays, and then told me that he would give me a $100 gift card if I came into the store to retrieve it.

I explained to Ken that did not want to come into the store, he asked me why not, and then I told him that Coronavirus, like he just mentioned, was the reason.  He said he could not waive the delivery fee I had paid for, but would credit my account $50.

All in all I spent over an hour on the phone trying to get this resolved.

< user>
100020157979271315317< /user>
< name>
Kaysie Snell</name>
<time>1277478855158<//time><rating>4</rating>< review>
They allow you to make payments on large items with no credit check. This is a wonderful idea for someone, such as myself, who has poor credit due to my divorce. I needed furniture quickly and I was able to get it through them. They are sales people and can be seen as pushy because their job is to sell... however they were very helpful every time I went in. I have a TV, couches, and washer/dryer through them. They will call you daily if you are a couple of days late on your payment but if you just let them know that you won't be able to make the payment for another few days they are totally ok with it. They do warn you though that they are still required to call daily until the payment is made. I just ignore those calls if it happens because we have already made the agreement and they know I'll be paying it another day. If you do ignore the calls and don't make an arangement with them, they will call your contacts on your application. That's understandable though... it's technically their product you are leasing and they want to ensure you haven't just run off with it. Make sure you call and make arrangements if you cannot make your payment on time.

The only downside to this program, of course, is that in the long run it is more expensive than just going and buying furniture. But... if your financial situation or credit is an obstacle I would definitely consider going to these guys. They're always friendly, helpful, and understanding.<//review>

<text>Let's face it: If you're going to the DPSS Office, you've got some issues. So does everyone else there. Which makes for a lot of cranky people on both sides of the windows. I found the staff at this office to be attentive and helpful once they knew what I needed.  That was the key.  If you show up and expect the System to roll out the welcome mat and anticipate your needs, well I think you are bound to be disappointed and frustrated. If you ask for help, my experience tells me you will get it promptly. There are at least 2 roaming staff in each large waiting area to help you if you are confused or don't know what forms you need or...well, any of the myriad of hurdles that face those needing assistance. If you are homeless do yourself a favor and visit the Long Beach Multi-Purpose Center just off of Anaheim and Harbor on 12th Street. That site has a DPSS worker available Mon-Wed-Fri (as of this posting 04-26-2016). This worker can screen you, provide you with the paperwork you will need and actually make an appointment for you with the office on Santa Fe Ave. This can save you a whole lot of time and bus tokens.</text>< Pics>

You can find not only the standard fare of snacks, groceries, and Japanese food staples but there are also restaurants as well as a whole floor of home goods, tshirts and so on. < Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Text>
Best Japanese food and kitchen supermarket I’ve been to outside of Japan.  They even have a Hawaiian products aisle.
Good produce selection, terrific sushi and seafood, and wonderful, noodles, sauces, and spices from Japan.  Best yet, many of the labels on the shelves explain and differentiate the products—very helpful when selecting a Shoyu sauce, soba noodle, or seaweed package.
Also, don’t forget to check upstairs for clothing, slippers, toys, suitcases, and other products.<//Text>

The best Japanese supermarket in Los Angeles. It's well stocked. I found everything I needed. Sea asparagus, fresh octopus, fish meatballs, etc. They have a big parking lot. It's crazy that they are associated with Don Quixote, a cheap department type store, which I went to in Tokyo.< /review>

< text>
I LOVE this store. They try their best to label everything in English to make it more accessible to folks.

If youre going to buy the plates make sure you show up before 7. At 7 pm they go on sale for 20% off but by then there's little to nothing left. People come in a little before 7 and stack their carts. Come earlier and pay full price if you really want to be able to have options.< /text>

< Review>
Very clean inside.  Due to Covid-19 protocol, limited people were allowed inside the market.  But the line moves very fast.  They have some good fresh vegetables, fruits and meat section.  They have this Passion Orange Guava (POG) in 1 quart carton at the refrigerator section.  They also have one of the best deal in bento boxes meal.  A box costs between 5.99 to 6.99.  Fresh sushi, maki rolls, all at a good price.<//Review>

< text>
The best Japanese supermarket. Not only is Tokyo Central designed culturally appreciate, but also you can find various Japanese food, snacks, and cultural heritage merchandise.

Tokyo Central Market is huge, clean, and well organized. Unfortunately, due to the COVID-19 pandemic era, the upper stores are closed.

When you are inclined to have Japanese food, enjoy a quick look at what Japanese culture looks like, come visit Tokyo Central Market.

You won’t be disappointed.<//text>

<text>The best prices in town for Japanese and Hawaii food items. It looks like the Don Quixote group is taking over, but I don't think that will impact the great prices. They also bring in unique food items and Japan regional fares. Right now it's strawberry season so they have cool but super expensive Japanese strawberries. The food court is also outstanding - the karaage chicken at Tenkatori is pretty awesome.
The down sides are minor stuff. I realize that they need to pack in product but I wish it was easier to maneuver the aisles. Many barely fit two carts going in opposing directions. Also the parking spaces tend to be on the tight side, and they don't have adequate very return stations.< /text>< GmapID>

< Text>
I had so much fun here! My husband and I got katsu from the food court, which was amazing. I haven't had katsu this good since I was in Japan. Then I had some fun browsing the retail items upstairs, ended up buying a few gifts for my friends who like kawaii things. The household items look pretty solid too, memory foam pillows, top of the line rice cookers, etc. I was kind of surprised they didn't have a bigger variety of Asian veggies (like 99 ranch, H-Mart). But they do have those Japanese strawberries (a real delicacy).< /Text>

<name>Leheart J.<//name><date>1609836256301<//date><rating>5< /rating>< review>
For a moment I thought I was inside Japan 🇯🇵 browsing Don Quiote / Tokyo. They really renovated this place and now it feels so Japanese you wonder 💭 if you are actually there and had memory loss about the airplane flight ✈️ and hotel. This grocery is nearly an exact replica, or slice of life, within Tokyo. I lived there for several years and the items this grocery carries along with its logistics is accurate to a T. Whoever managed this place, I could tell, is very educated and very, VERY competent. You could even come here as a “Japan travel destination” during this covid-19 madness we Los Angelinos are all going through. Just come here, this might as well be Japan.< /review>

< Text>
My wife, who is Japanese, and I started to go to TCM Redondo Beach Blvd and Artesia Blvd at the beginning of the pandemic. Now we rarely go to the Ralph's in our neighborhood. The meat selection at TCM is 1000 times better than Ralph's for cooking Japanese food because it is sliced properly. Moreover, the fruits and vegetables are the freshest and cheapest. The Mammoth Bakery inside the TCM on RB Blvd is our favorite place to buy sliced bread, perfect for breakfast toast. We can get Crystal Geyser Water for only 79 cents a gallon! We can also get very Japanese vegetable, fruit, and herb we need there. The Artesia Blvd one has great restaurants and a bakery inside. They also have the best selection of meat and bento, IMO. I loved their karaage chicken deli, but they closed it. Their 2nd floor has character goods, cooking appliances, and clothes. My wife occasionally gets stuff up there. I love their various "fairs." We got a lot of stuff during their KAGOSHIMA Fair. It is so cool to be able to get the real taste of Japan here in So Cal.</Text>

< gmap_id>
0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2< /gmap_id>
< Text>
The BEST in LA!
Seriously Huge and Packed with just about Everything you could want from a Japanese supermarket and goods store. Makeup, detergent, furniture, stationary, gifts, home goods, electronic dictionaries, air conditioners, cookware, kitchen goods, stuffed animals, phone accessories, car scents, etc etc etc. Just Huge and the biggest, most well-stocked shop period among all of the Tokyo Central, Nijiya, Mitsuwa, and other Japanese supermarket centers in Los Angeles.
A handful of restaurants from takoyaki to karage for takeout.
Latest corona remodel gets rid of the antique furniture $$$, closed the dining (can still take out), adds a big stationary section with more pens and pencils than Kinokuniya, even more housewares, beauty supplies, tons of boxed take out meals, etc.
And prices are among the lowest at Japanese markets in L.A.
Seriously, the ONLY Japanese supermarket you need to shop at - a mini Bic Camera or Yodabashi!!<//Text>

<Review>$2.87 for a bag of ORGANiC ginger; as of february 2019.

This market caters to customers that have high standards for quality produce. The mandarin fruits are consistently of high quality. Its not the cheapest market to shop for produce but there are always deals for some of the items. You can save yourself some serious dollars if you keep checking what is on sale and when.

Ping me for any additional questions. I am happy to help.

Feel free to hit the Like button if my review has been useful for you?
Thank you!< /Review></record></dataset><record>

< text>
Pricey for what I'm used to for an Asian grocery chain, but it might be the location (Hmart is pricier here/CA than the ones where I lived in MD/DC). Sushi/sashimi fish department has a great selection, and it's where I discovered the sashimi version of "ends and pieces: price reduced". Quite a lot of options for a fancy meat connoisseur, too.

They're worth visiting just to see all the kitsch/kawaii upstairs. I'm not much of a collector, but I've heard from others that the prices are competitive and the finds good.</text>

< Review>
This used to be marukai but I guess they got bought out by Tokyo central. It's still pretty much the same though except the dining area got upgraded especially the outdoor part. This market has a big Japanese cosmetics, lifestyle, home goods area which I love! I think if I ranked the Japanese market this would be on top closely after nijiya. Mitsuwa is prettier but it doesn't have as many items. Also this market has the best chicken karaage in their food court. Always super crowded ( which is bad during this pandemic) but theres a reason why so many people go here.< /Review>

<user_id>106146170388544342263< /user_id>< pictures>
None</pictures>
< Text>
Love this japanese market, it has everything you need if you are in need of Japanese food and food. Has basic everyday household Japanese appliances, rice cooker, humidifier, hot water maker, dishes, cups, and a bunch of other cute useful Japanese things you want but you don't need. Awesome food selection, lots of reasonably priced fresh vegetables and fruit. Has organics and imports from Japan. Fresh fish from Japan and local, at reasonable prices. The meat selection is amazing the best meat you could probably get anywhere. The snacks and all Japanese ingredients you need they will have it at a good price.

They also have a food court area if you come during the busy hours of the day. The pork buns are amazing. Sometimes it gets busy so pick wisely what time if the day you decided to go. The structure is difficult to get in on Artesia. I use to pass it a few times before i was able to identify it. It's surrounded by a green fence all around.</Text>

< rate>
4<//rate>
<review>This place was originally known as Marukai, I'm not sure when they changed the name. Inside you can find a couple small restaurants, groceries, and novelty products.

Downstairs, they have a large selection of meats, vegetables and drinks/beer. Also available are many Japanese snacks and candy (these alone make a trip worth it in my opinion).

Upstairs, their products range from furniture to figurines. They have a lot of novelty and comfort items, including the full size pajamas with a hood known as kigurumi, and blind boxes containing random cute figurines.

This store can make for a fun browsing experience, and can also satisfy a grocery trip. I can only caution that with all of the neat things they have here is that you might spend more money than you plan to.<//review>< Pics>

<review>I love this Japanese market. It is HUGE. The sushi section is awesome. It rivals any restaurant sushi for 2/3 of the price. Fresh and yummy. Besides all the great Japanese and Hawaiian grocery items they have a whole area with plates, rice cookers, and kitchenware as well as a gift and pop toy section upstairs. They also have a wellness area.

I also like the fresh mochi and desserts they each week from Fugetsu Do and the hot food restaurants inside. From karage to Gindaco, a ramen place, a tonkatsu place, and a Japanese pastry shop. They also have a croquette and onigiri deli in the corner as well as karage.

If you want bug cuts of fish for sushi, simply go to the butchery in the back of the store.

The Tokyo Central in Torrance is much smaller and driving to the one in Gardena is worth it.<//review>< resp>

<user>116733847310475342493< /user><username>J & A<//username>< Date>
1562889645800<//Date>
< rate>
5<//rate>
< review>
This place has everything you can think of for a Japanese market. It's really a mega store. Deli, fresh sushi counter, a few fast food stands, inside & outside eating areas, grocery store with impressive selections of Japanese goods, very fresh produce, well stocked liquor area (could not find Okinawan saki unfortunately). The downstairs also houses a separate cosmetics section, it is so big it is a little overwhelming & I honestly didn't know what half the stuff was meant for since I'm not able to read the letters. It also has a separate appliances area with rice cookers and small things like that. The upstairs has all the fun stuff. Things like kimonos (some moderate priced used ones) wooden sandals, cute hair clips, Zen gardens, lucky cats, dolls, trinkets, stuffed animals, crazy socks, kigurumi (onesies), costumes, models, Pokemon stuff.
Also, everyone that works here is super helpful if you have questions about anything so don't hesitate to ask.
Overall, you could spend a few hours exploring this place, shopping, having lunch & have a great time doing it.< /review>

<text>Went in Tokyo central Market place of business in Uniform to get change for $5.
My badge in clear sight.

As I approached the register,
i noted there was a guest services.

There were 2 women there.

I spoke to the older of the 2.

Without hesitation she quickly replied no.

I noted the registers all around were giving change.

I repeated are you sure?

She did not give a reason.
For example,

I had to " Purchase" something,
or it's their policy not to give Change!

She did neither, nor offer any explanation.

Her eyes and Body language suggested me out the door quickly.
I am on duty,
well groomed, dressed in uniform.

The wrong nationality in my opinion.

As I sit here writing this,
I can still see the the look in her eyes.
Her body language left me feeling..

Like a Foreigner in his Homeland!

It's kind of ironic, as I was born
in Japan & am of Indian and English descent!
Therefore I am a Native to this land...

Tonight and throughout the holidays I will put the word out to my Family, Friends and the Department Not!

To shop @ Tokyo Central Market.
On Artesia Blvd in Gardena CA</text></record>

< Time>
1544475653607< /Time>
<username>John Jiao< /username><Text>I'm a Hawaii native, so I've been exposed to a lot of American-Japanese food/culture/etc, and this place is easily the BEST Japanese market I've ever been to. If you're into Hawaiian food, there's multiple aisles of stuff I've literally never seen outside of Hawaii before --- authentic portugeuse sausage, lau lau, every single type of sugary drink (POG, passion orange, etc), even frozen Zippys meals (!!!)

From a Japanese standpoint, everything is not only directly imported, but there are little English descriptions of all the foods on the price labels. All the staff are super courteous, and the food court attached is out of this world!

A real shining star here is the sushi --- it's cheaper, fresher, and tastier than you'll be able to get anywhere else that I've ever seen. There's also an authentic Japanese curry stand in the back corner where you can get all kinds of amazing curry dishes. The food court has some of the best karaage chicken I've ever had, and this is the first time I've seen an authentic takoyaki stand in LA.

All in all, amazing service, amazing prices, and a must-go for anybody who loves Japanese food.< /Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Resp>None</Resp>< GmapID>
0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2< /GmapID>

< rate>
5</rate>
<time>1535536752354</time><gmap_id>0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2</gmap_id><Pics>None< /Pics>< text>
Tokyo Central, my favorite Japanese grocery store is the mother of all Japanese supermarkets having not only the first floor w/ mostly comestibles & dry goods, but also having a second floor that specializes in furniture & Japanese objets d'art.

Nijiya is a good place to run in fast to get a few items, but for  the sheer variety of goods such as reasonable cosmetics, Sakè (sah keh), Japanese beers, Sho-chu-/Japanese lower alcohol Vodkas, snacks, produce, Japanese food in cans, frozen, plastic, produce Tokyo Central can't be beat.

There is something for everybody, at least for those interested in Japanese products.  If you're in here for the first time prepare to stay for about an hour to see what is available & acquant yourself to the layout. The proof is in the pudding; you have to go there.</text>

<Date>1409949486922< /Date><rating>4< /rating>< review>
Boo to memberships. That being said, you can still enter and purchase items without a membership. They will charge an extra dollar and you don’t get the sale prices, but at least you can still shop. They have one day memberships available if needed. The top floor is filled with Japanese items such as traditional clothing, furniture and unique décor items and the main floor is filled to the brim with Japanese and Hawaiian groceries. On weekends there are sample food carts dishing out simple Japanese dishes to try. The food court is small but sufficient. Avoid at all costs around New Years.<//review>

<Review>This place has it all as far as a Japanese style market goes.

It has all the dry goods to make whats popular at home. All the frozen goods to take home and eat and also a nice little fiod court area to get some pretty decent food.

The Store also has a floral area and a toys/Japanese hobby section even have the paints you need to paint them. Pretty cool!

There lots of cool japanese nicknacks and little gifts if you want to gift some one something cool.

The makeup area is massive. I think this is the second biggest part of the store. Ir has everything iou would need as far as makup is concerned. Cheap too. I mean its not a Sephora but you get the picture.

There is a ready food are that is nice to pick up a quick sushi roll or even a nagiri or rice roll. Im surprised i never have been here sooner. I always just go to Marukai, But this place I beleive is a branch off of Marukai in Torrance. So a hit!

If your looking for something Japanese. This is the place. For sure!</Review><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Response>

<Text>One of, if not THE, best Japanese supermarkets in the Los Angeles area. My family has been going here for years and, more often than not, we always find what we need. The prices can skew a little high on some items, I find that I can usually do my produce shopping elsewhere and save a little, but in general the prices are fine. It can get a little cramped inside on weekends and you should absolutely be prepared for a wait in the checkout line. For years I shopped at their satellite store in West Covina (closed now, sadly) and while it was much closer that was about the only thing it had up on the Gardena store. Consistently clean and, aside from one experience with a belligerent employee, the staff is great. I've tried most of their competitors over the years and have consistently come back to Marukai.<//Text><time>1423595906574</time><gmapID>0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2< /gmapID><Pictures>None<//Pictures><UserId.>113044265628566895776</UserId.></record></dataset><record>

<Name>Cat Manabat</Name><Review>I heart Murakai so much. I am much closer to the Little Tokyo location, but what I love about the Gardena Murakai is that it is way bigger and never gets as crowded as the Little Tokyo one. (We all want to avoid that moment when you and an elderly lady are eyeing that last packet of whatever...and you briefly wonder if it's socially acceptable to elbow her out of the way.)

I usually pick up saimin ingredients, my favorite snacks, and other packaged items so I can't speak for any of the hot food or even packaged pastries there...but they always have what I need and then some. Sure, I need a mini stapler and a panda-shaped mug. Sure, I need taro pancake mix and strawberry Kit Kats. Why the eff not? The cashiers are super nice as well.

I did knock off a star because I happened to use the bathroom once and it was...not pretty. < Review>
(Translated by Google) Very well stocked Japanese supermarket. They sell prepared food ready to go. You will find all kinds of ingredients to prepare traditional Japanese food. The food prepared while later it is, they lower the price as they do in the supermarkets in Japan. If you want to try traditional Japanese fast food this is the best place. I visited it with my nephews and we brought many snacks and instant soups to try at home, my nephews were delighted and we returned the next day to buy more. Due to the covid they offer masks to be able to enter in case they forgot. I found some merchandising products from Studio Ghibli. The supermarket is worth a visit. The next time I travel to Los Angeles I will visit them again.

(Original)
Supermercado japonés muy bien surtido. Venden comida preparada lista para llevar. Encontrarán todo tipo de ingredientes para preparar comida tradicional japonesa. La comida preparada mientras más tarde es, le rebajan el precio como lo hacen en los supermercados en Japón. Si desean probar comida rápido tradicional japonesa este es el mejor lugar. Lo visité con mis sobrinos y llevamos muchos snacks y sopas instantaneas para probar en casa, mis sobrinos quedaron encantados y regresamos el día siguiente a comprar más. Por el covid ofrecen mascarillas para poder ingresar por si se les olvidó.  Encontré algunos productos merchandising de Studio Ghibli. Vale la pena visitar el supermercado. La próxima vez que viaje a Los Angeles volveré visitarlos.< /Review>
